Innes, of Croft, to whom, about 1928 (about 8 years ago), it had been given by one of his farm employees, named Morton, who died about 1933 or 4 (= "2 or 3 years ago") aged 69, and who had been a farm lad at or near Egton when 'a pal' of his, another farm lad, found the dagger when herding up sheep on the moor. C.F.C.H.),Brought by Dr Elgee to the British Museum, Nov. 1936, when this card was filled in and its drawing made, and the dagger was submitted to Dr. H.J. Plenderleith, B.M. site: England, Yorkshire, Wakefield (near), Woodnook., Found while excavating a lock at a depth of 24 feet, 1842. Found in gravel bed above shale and in thick alluvial deposits
description: The edges of the blade of slightly ogival outline; low-ridged midrib running the whole length of the blade; a hollow fluted groove runs parallel with and close to the cutting edge; behind this is a rounded ridge with V-shaped hollow beyond, defining outer edge of midrib.  Down each side of midrib are three cast or engraved parallel lines, and across the base of midrib three rows of engraved chevron ornament and one row of crossed zigzags; three large rivets at base of blade.  Beautiful preservation and finish.
publications: Bowman, W. (ed.) 1855, Reliquiae Antiquae Eboracenses, pp 39-40

At 8 ft. the ? primary burial was an urn in a rough 'cist of stones',mouth down over burnt bones with a 'drinking cup' (presumably food vessel in W.C. Mus.).
description: Knife or dagger with point missing and probably much of left-hand side (on drawing),gone. One rivet (rectangular in section) corroded in place, projecting equally each side and,both heads bent slightly towards heel. Rivet heads flat; do not appear to have been hammered,out.
